SPOTSCANNER(1)               User Commands              SPOTSCANNER(1)

NAME
       spotscanner - quantitative analysis of fungal spot-test plates

SYNOPSIS
       spotscanner [-v] [-e] [-r]
                  [-o {manual,marker-pdf,marker-tex,citation}]
                  -a {pipette,replicator}
                  [-s SINGLE | -m]
                  [-t 1..10]

DESCRIPTION
       SpotScanner is a command-line tool for quantitative analysis of
       fungal spot-test plates. It detects a printed marker on the
       plate, segments the image into a fixed grid, and measures colony
       growth in each spot, outputting results as CSV files and
       diagnostic images.

       The tool is designed for fungal genetics experiments (e.g.
       Neurospora spot tests) using either multi-channel replicators
       or manual pipetting.

OPTIONS
       -v, --version
              Show version information and citation, then exit.

       -e, --example
              Show short usage examples and exit.

       -r, --readme
              View the SpotScanner manual (spotscanner.1) with less.
              This is essentially equivalent to running “less” on the
              installed manual file.

       -o, --output {manual,marker-pdf,marker-tex,citation}
              Open or output auxiliary resources.

              manual
                     Print a text manual (man-style) to standard
                     output. This is convenient for use with pipes,
                     for example:

                            spotscanner -o manual | less

              marker-pdf
                     Open the printable marker PDF with the system
                     viewer.

              marker-tex
                     Print the LaTeX source of the marker to standard
                     output and write it to marker.tex in the current
                     directory. You can then run:

                            lualatex marker.tex

                     to generate marker.pdf.

              citation
                     Print a BibTeX entry for SpotScanner and write it
                     to spotscanner.bib in the current directory.

       -a, --analyze {pipette,replicator}
              Choose the plate layout. This option is required for
              image analysis.

              pipette
                     4×6 matrix layout for manually pipetted plates.

              replicator
                     8×12 matrix layout for multi-channel replicators.

       -s, --single SINGLE
              Analyze only the specified image file. SINGLE should be a
              .jpg/.JPG/.jpeg file in the current directory.

       -m, --multi
              Analyze all .jpg/.JPG/.jpeg images in the current
              directory.

              Exactly one of --single or --multi must be specified
              when analyzing images.

       -t, --threshold N
              Threshold for marker recognition, where N is an integer
              from 1 to 10. The default is 7 if this option is
              omitted. Internally this is interpreted as N/10. Higher
              values generally make marker detection stricter.

MODES
       Pipette mode (4×6)
              In pipette mode, SpotScanner segments the plate into a
              4×6 grid corresponding to manually pipetted spots.

       Replicator mode (8×12)
              In replicator mode, SpotScanner segments the plate into
              an 8×12 grid corresponding to a typical replicator
              layout.

TYPICAL WORKFLOWS
       Generate and print the marker
              To obtain the printable marker PDF:

                     spotscanner -o marker-pdf

              To regenerate the marker from LaTeX:

                     spotscanner -o marker-tex
                     lualatex marker.tex

              This produces marker.pdf in the current directory.

       Analyze a single image (pipette mode)
              1. Place the printed marker under the spot-test plate.
              2. Take a photograph of the plate including the entire
                 marker.
              3. Copy the image (e.g. plate1.jpg) into a working
                 directory.
              4. Run:

                     spotscanner -a pipette -s plate1.jpg

              SpotScanner will detect the marker, align the image,
              segment it into a 4×6 grid, and output:

                     plate1_converted.png
                     plate1_results.csv

              The CSV file typically includes columns such as:

                     Time, Image, Threshold, row, column, Colony

       Analyze all images in a directory (replicator mode)
              1. Copy all plate images (plate1.jpg, plate2.jpg, ...)
                 into one directory.
              2. Run:

                     spotscanner -a replicator -m

              SpotScanner will process each .jpg/.JPG/.jpeg file,
              creating *_converted.png and *_results.csv files, and
              grouping outputs into timestamped directories such as:

                     converted_YYYY-MM-DD_HH-MM-SS/
                     results_YYYY-MM-DD_HH-MM-SS/

FILES
       INSTALL_ROOT/spotscanner/
              Python package containing the SpotScanner code.

       INSTALL_ROOT/marker/
              Marker images used for recognition.

       INSTALL_ROOT/template/marker.pdf
              Printable marker.

       INSTALL_ROOT/template/marker.tex
              LaTeX source of the marker.

       INSTALL_ROOT/template/spotscanner.1
              Text manual in man(1) style.

ENVIRONMENT
       SPOTSCANNER_ROOT
              If set, this directory is used as the install root
              containing spotscanner/, marker/, and template/.
              Otherwise, the install root is inferred from the location
              of the spotscanner package.

